The '''AN/TPS-80 Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar''' (G/ATOR) is the [[United States Marine Corps]] next-generation Air Surveillance/[[Air Defense]] and [[Air Traffic Control]] (ATC) Radar. The mobile [[active electronically scanned array]] [[radar system]] is being developed and produced by [[Northrop Grumman#Electronic System|Northrop Grumman]] and was expected to reach [[initial operating capability]] in August 2016.<ref name="DTIC">{{cite web |date=16 April 2014 |title=Selected Acquisition Report (SAR), Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR) |url=https://apps.dtic.mil/sti/pdfs/ADA613516.pdf |accessdate=21 October 2015 |website=Defense Technical Information Center |publisher=Department of Defense}}</ref> Initial production began in June of 2019.<ref name="20251202DN">{{cite news |last1=South |first1=Todd |title=Marines more than halfway through fielding of new 360-degree radar |url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2025/04/28/marines-more-than-halfway-through-fielding-of-new-360-degree-radar/ |access-date=2 December 2025 |work=[[Defense News]] |publisher=[[Michael Reinstein]] |date=28 April 2025}}</ref> In October of 2025, one unit was controversially deployed to the Island nation of [[Trinidad and Tobago]], which is just 7 miles off the coast of [[Venezuela]].<ref name="20251202TG">{{cite news |last1=Duncan |first1=Natricia |last2=Haynes |first2=Kejan |title=Radar revelation stokes fears Caribbean could be drawn into US-Venezuela crisis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/dec/02/us-venezuela-crisis-trinidad-tobago |access-date=2 December 2025 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=2 December 2025}}</ref>

In accordance with the [[Joint Electronics Type Designation System]] (JETDS), the "''AN/TPS-80''" designation represents the 80th design of an Army-Navy [[Electronics|electronic device]] for ground transportable search radar system. The JETDS system also now is used to name all [[Department of Defense]] electronic systems.

==Mission and description==
The Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR) is a single material solution for the mobile Multi-Role Radar System and Ground Weapons Locating Radar (GWLR) requirements. It is a [[3D radar|three-dimensional]], medium/long-range multi-role radar designed to detect [[unmanned aerial vehicles|unmanned aerial systems]], [[cruise missiles]], air-breathing targets, [[rockets]], [[artillery]], and [[Mortar (weapon)|mortars]]. G/ATOR is designed to fulfil expeditionary needs across the [[Marine Air-Ground Task Force]] spectrum, replacing five legacy radar systems with a single solution.<ref name=Gourley>{{cite web|last1=Gourley|first1=Scott R.|title=Ground-based Air Defense and Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar|url=http://www.marcorsyscom.marines.mil/Portals/105/PELandSystem/GATOR_090412.pdf|website=Program Executive Officer Land Systems|publisher=Marine Corps Systems Command|date=Summer 2012|accessdate=21 October 2015}}{{Dead link|date=July 2025 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  

The five Marine Corps legacy radar systems being replaced by this multi-function capability include: the [[AN/TPS-63]] (air defense), AN/TPS-73 (air-traffic control), [[AN/MPQ-62]] (short-range air defense), AN/TPQ-46 ([[Counter-battery fire|counter-fire]] target acquisition) and UPS-3 (target tracking).<ref name=Burgess>{{cite journal|last1=Burgess|first1=Richard R.|title=A Radar for All Missions|journal=Seapower|date=November 2010|volume=53|issue=11|pages=42–44|url=http://www.seapower-digital.com/seapower/201011?pg=44#pg44|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307105017/http://www.seapower-digital.com/seapower/201011?pg=44#pg44|archive-date=March 7, 2016|url-status=usurped|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> Additionally, it will augment the [[AN/TPS-59]] long-range radar.<ref name=DOTE/>

The Program Executive Office (PEO), Land Systems Marine Corps is executing the G/ATOR program, as an evolutionary acquisition program of four capabilities, referred to as blocks.<ref name=DOTE/>
* Block 1 completes the primary material system acquisition, and can support the short-range air defense and air surveillance mission, as well as provide an Air Defence/Surveillance Radar (AD/SR) capability to the MAGTF Commander.
* Block 2 includes software to perform the missions of ground counter-battery/fire control (Ground Locating Weapons Radar).
* Block 3 capabilities are not currently defined or resourced, and have been deferred indefinitely.
* Block 4 provides air traffic control capabilities (Expeditionary Airport Surveillance Radar).
[[File:GATOR.png|thumb|G/ATOR System Configuration]]
G/ATOR provides real-time radar measurement data to the Tactical Air Operations Module, Common Aviation Command and Control System (CAC2S), Composite Tracking Network, and [[Advanced Field Artillery Tactical Data System]].<ref name=Keller1410/>

The G/ATOR baseline system configuration consists of three subsystems:<ref name=DOTE/>
* Communications Equipment Group (CEG). The CEG provides the ability to communicate with and control the radar and is mounted on a [[High Mobility Multi-purpose Wheeled Vehicle]].
* Radar Equipment Group (REG). The REG consists of a phased-array radar mounted on an integrated trailer. The trailer is towed by the [[Medium Tactical Vehicle Replacement]] (MTVR).
* Power Equipment Group (PEG). The PEG includes a 60-kilowatt generator and associated power cables mounted on a pallet. The generator pallet is carried by the MTVR.
