==Development==
[[File:AN TPS-80 Ground Air Task Oriented Radar.webm|300px|thumb|AN/TPS-80 Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar, at Marine Corps Air Station Yuma]]
Development of the G/ATOR began in September 2005 when the Marine Corps awarded a $7.9 million contract to [[Northrop Grumman Electronic Systems]]. Initial design requirements required planning for short-range air surveillance, counter-battery fire and target acquisition, and sensor networking.  The requirement required Block 1 to allow for incremental implementation of the following blocks without equipment or software redesign.<ref name=Keller1410>{{cite journal|last1=Keller|first1=John|title=After nine years, Marine Corp finally may have full production of G/ATOR radar in sight|journal=Military Aerospace Electronics Magazine|date=October 24, 2014|url=https://www.militaryaerospace.com/articles/2014/10/gator-radar-production.html|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref>

In 2009, a $14 million cost overrun for the G/ATOR, was attributed to [[requirements creep]] and the increasing cost of scarce materials required in advanced electronic components. In 2012 the Marine Corps and Northrop Grumman began Block 2 development, beginning with upgrading the Block 1 equipment and software for performing GWLR requirements.<ref name=Keller1410/><ref name=Keller1503/>

The G/ATOR program obtained a successful Milestone C decision in March 2014. In October 2014, a 207.3 million dollar [[low rate initial production]] (LRIP) contract was awarded to Northrop Grumman for the first four systems.<ref name=Keller1410/><ref name=Concepts>{{cite web|title=AN/TPS-80 Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR)|url=https://marinecorpsconceptsandprograms.com/programs/aviation/antps-80-groundair-task-oriented-radar-gator|website=Marine Corps Concepts and Programs|publisher=United States Marine Corps|accessdate=21 October 2015|date=18 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070551/https://marinecorpsconceptsandprograms.com/programs/aviation/antps-80-groundair-task-oriented-radar-gator|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In March 2015, another contract worth $113 million was awarded to produce two additional systems to be delivered in October 2017.<ref name=Keller1503>{{cite journal|last1=Keller|first1=John|title=Latest order for Marine Corps G/ATOR radar systems brings total number of radars to six|journal=Military Aerospace Electronics Magazine|date=March 17, 2015|url=https://www.militaryaerospace.com/articles/2015/03/gator-radar-order.html|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=AMRPulseAug15>{{cite news|last1=Withington |first1=Thomas |title=AMR Pulse - Radar |url=http://www.asianmilitaryreview.com/category/amr-pulse/ |accessdate=21 October 2015 |work=Asian Military Review }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

In September 2015, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $58.7 million contract to incorporate and test the GWLR mode for the G/ATOR.<ref name=GWLR>{{cite news|title=Northrop Grumman Receives Contract to Add Ground Capabilities to AN/TPS-80 Ground/Air Task-Oriented Radar|url=http://www.irconnect.com/noc/press/pages/news_releases.html?d=10152245|accessdate=21 October 2015|publisher=Globe Newswire}}</ref>

In September 2016, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $375 million contract for nine additional LRIP systems that will incorporate [[gallium nitride]] (GaN) technology.<ref>{{cite news|title=Northrop Grumman Awarded Contract for Nine GaN G/ATOR Systems|url=http://news.northropgrumman.com/news/releases/northrop-grumman-awarded-contract-for-nine-gan-g-ator-systems|accessdate=11 October 2016|publisher=Northrop Grumman}}</ref>

In June 2019, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $958 million contract for full-rate production of 30 GaN G/ATOR Systems.<ref>{{cite news|title=Northrop Grumman Awarded Contract to Provide Marine Corps Full-Rate Production G/ATOR Radar Systems|url=https://news.northropgrumman.com/news/releases/northrop-grumman-awarded-contract-to-provide-marine-corps-full-rate-production-gator-radar-systems|accessdate=9 August 2019|publisher=Northrop Grumman}}</ref>

A total of 60 G/ATOR systems are planned for procurement through 2029.<ref name=DTIC /><ref name="20251202DN" /><ref name=DOTE>{{cite web|title=Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR)|url=http://www.dote.osd.mil/pub/reports/FY2013/pdf/navy/2013gator.pdf|website=The Office of the Director, Operational Test & Evaluation|publisher=Director, Operational Test & Evaluation|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>

In December 2019, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $188 million contract, for the firm-fixed-price portion of a previously awarded contract (M67854-19-C-0043). This modification is for the purchase of six Gallium Nitride full-rate-production systems and associated travel in support of Program Executive Officer Land Systems, Quantico, Virginia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Contracts For Dec. 6, 2019|url=https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Contracts/Contract/Article/2034460/source/GovDelivery/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207132201/https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Contracts/Contract/Article/2034460/source/GovDelivery/|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 7, 2019|access-date=7 December 2019|publisher=Department of Defense}}</ref>

Saab is subcontracted by Northrop Grumman Corporation and has delivered major subsystems and assemblies as well as software since Lot1 and has been part of the development since originally contracted in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.saab.com/newsroom/press-releases/2015/saab-to-supply-key-components-in-support-of-the-u.s.-marine-corps-groundair-task-oriented-radar-gator-program |title=Saab to Supply Key Components in Support of the U.S. Marine Corps Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR) Program |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031164750/https://www.saab.com/newsroom/press-releases/2015/saab-to-supply-key-components-in-support-of-the-u.s.-marine-corps-groundair-task-oriented-radar-gator-program |archive-date=2020-10-31 |url-status=live |date=Feb 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.saab.com/newsroom/press-releases/2016/saab-receives-contract-for-components-to-the-u.s.-marine-corps-groundair-task-oriented-radar-program |title=Saab Receives Contract for Components to the U.S. Marine Corps' Ground/Air Task-Oriented Radar Program |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201025164415/https://www.saab.com/newsroom/press-releases/2016/saab-receives-contract-for-components-to-the-u.s.-marine-corps-groundair-task-oriented-radar-program |archive-date=2020-10-25 |url-status=live |date=Dec 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.saab.com/markets/united-states/news-and-press-releases/2019/saab-receives-order-for-components-for-the-u.s.-marine-corps-gator-radar |title=Saab Receives Order for Components for the U.S. Marine Corps G/ATOR Radar |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201027234023/https://www.saab.com/markets/united-states/news-and-press-releases/2019/saab-receives-order-for-components-for-the-u.s.-marine-corps-gator-radar |archive-date=2020-10-27 |url-status=live |date=Dec 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.saab.com/newsroom/press-releases/2020/saab-receives-order-for-radar-system-components-for-the-u.s.-marine-corps |title=Saab receives order for radar system components for the U.S. Marine Corps |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201025110617/https://www.saab.com/newsroom/press-releases/2020/saab-receives-order-for-radar-system-components-for-the-u.s.-marine-corps |archive-date=2020-10-25 |url-status=live |date=Sep 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.saab.com/globalassets/cision/documents/2020/20200923-saab-far-bestallning-pa-radarkomponenter-till-amerikanska-marinen-sv-0-3778430.pdf |lang=swedish |title=Saab får beställning på radarkomponenter till amerikanska marinen |trans-title=Saab receives order for radar system components for the U.S. Marine Corps |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201225003127/https://www.saab.com/globalassets/cision/documents/2020/20200923-saab-far-bestallning-pa-radarkomponenter-till-amerikanska-marinen-sv-0-3778430.pdf |archive-date=2020-12-25 |url-status=live |publisher=Saab AB}}</ref>

==Main characteristics==
{{Promotional section|date=July 2025}}
* Multipurpose tracking and surveillance [[S-band]] {{cvt|2–4|GHz|cm}} [[3D radar]]
* Detects [[Fixed-wing aircraft|fixed-]] and [[rotary-wing aircraft]], [[cruise missiles]], and [[UAVs]]
* Performs [[Air traffic control|ATC]] and [[counter-battery radar|fire finder]] roles
* High mobility, transportability, and reliability
* The entire system can be airlifted into an operational site by three [[CH-53E Super Stallion]] heavy-lift helicopters or [[Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey#Variants|MV-22B Osprey]] tilt-rotor aircraft, or by a single [[C-130 Hercules]] transport.
* The system is required to be set up on-site within 45 minutes.
* Provides identification of friendly aircraft using a Telephonics AN/UPX-44 IFF ([[Identification Friend or Foe]]) integrated with the main radar.

